Certainly! Here is a revised version of the test case using a try-catch block to handle the scenario:

```java
import static org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions.fail;

import java.util.HashMap;
import org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;

class AlarmPostingUtilsTest {

    @Test
    void evaluateExpression_withInvalidExpression() {
        // Arrange
        String expression = "%invalidExpression%";
        AlarmPostingUtils alarmPostingUtils = new AlarmPostingUtils();

        try {
            // Act
            alarmPostingUtils.evaluateExpression(expression, new HashMap<>());
            // If no exception is thrown, the test should fail
            fail("Expected an Exception to be thrown, but nothing was thrown.");
        } catch (Exception e) {
            // Assert
            // Exception is expected, so the test passes if this block is executed
        }
    }
}
```

In this version, we manually check if an exception is thrown using a try-catch block. If the exception is not thrown, the test fails by calling `fail()`. If the exception is thrown, the catch block handles it, indicating that the test passes.